    <listApp>
      <app loc="37">
        <lem>-mahārājādhirāja-parameśvara<supplied reason="omitted">ḥ</supplied></lem>
        <note>SR does not emend to a nominative, but adds a note, anchored between the words <foreign>mahārājādhirāja</foreign> and <foreign>parameśvara</foreign>, which says <q><foreign>rājaparameśvara</foreign></q>. He may have intended an emendation to <foreign>mahārājādhirāja-rājaparameśvara</foreign>, but this is unwarranted.</note>
      </app>
      <app loc="39">
        <lem>śrīmati</lem>
        <note>The beginning of this passage fits the requirements of <foreign>āryā</foreign> or a related moraic metre, but unless SR’s edition is seriously wrong, the passage as a whole is prose.</note>
      </app>
      <app loc="39">
        <lem>paya<choice><sic>ḥ</sic><corr>ḥ</corr></choice>-pay<choice><sic>e</sic><corr>o</corr></choice><lb n="40" break="no"/><choice><sic>d</sic><corr>dh</corr></choice>i-</lem>
        <note>SR suggests the emdendation <foreign>payaḥ-payonidhi</foreign>, but unless <foreign>ni</foreign> is present in the original and omitted from his edition, its addition is unwarranted. I suspect that <foreign>rpa</foreign> is actually meant to represent <foreign>ḫpa</foreign> (with <foreign>r</foreign> used in the Devanagari to replace <foreign>ṟ</foreign>, which in turn may have been used in SR’s manuscript to replace <foreign>ḫ</foreign>).</note>
      </app>
      <app loc="41">
        <lem>-śālī</lem>
        <rdg source="bib:SubbaRao1956-1958_01">-śāli</rdg>
      </app>
      <app loc="42">
        <lem>-guṇ<choice><sic>ār</sic><corr>aḥ</corr></choice></lem>
        <rdg source="bib:SubbaRao1956-1958_01">-guṇ<choice><sic>ār</sic><corr>ān</corr></choice></rdg>
        <note>I suspect that <foreign>rpi</foreign> stands for <foreign>ḫpi</foreign> (cf. the note to line 39). If, in addition, <foreign>ā</foreign> is a typo for <foreign>a</foreign>, then the reading needs no emendation.</note>
      </app>
      <app loc="42">
        <lem source="bib:SubbaRao1956-1958_01">anukurvan nannaka-</lem>
        <note>I follow the segmentation of the ARIE report, where this name is said to be Nannaka. Theoretically, the text could also be segmented into <foreign>anukurvann annaka-</foreign>. SR’s commentary ignores this name and says the son of Poleyana was called Anupamaguṇa.</note>
      </app>
      <app loc="43">
        <lem source="bib:SubbaRao1956-1958_01">āytakaṁbāyāś</lem>
        <note>The ARIE report gives this name as Aytakaṁbāyā, though this may be a typo.</note>
      </app>
      <app loc="45">
        <lem>-śirodarpaṇa-</lem>
        <note>SR emends this word to <foreign>-śirodarpaṇa-</foreign>, the only difference being that in his edition the word is written with a Devanagari <foreign>ra</foreign> and <foreign>virāma</foreign>, while in his footnote (also in Devanagari) it is with the ligature <foreign>rpa</foreign>. An <foreign>upadhmānīya</foreign> may be involved (cf. the note to line 39), but I cannot offer a better reading.</note>
      </app>
      <app loc="45">
        <lem source="bib:SubbaRao1956-1958_01"><sic>dhvajāmālparepoṣaṇa</sic></lem>
        <note>I cannot suggest an improvement here and give the reading exactly as printed in SR’s edition. I suspect that scribal errors are coupled here with misreadings by SR, and possibly also in the preceding words <foreign>nara-śirodarpaṇa-</foreign> and in <foreign>praśasti-</foreign> in the next line.</note>
      </app>
      <app loc="45">
        <lem>candyana</lem>
        <rdg source="bib:SubbaRao1956-1958_01">cand<surplus>y</surplus>ana</rdg>
        <note>I find the emendation unwarranted; the name is probably a variant of <foreign>candeṇa</foreign> (found in the <ref target="DHARMA_INSVengiCalukya00030.xml">Ārumbāka grant of Bādapa</ref>).</note>
      </app>
      <app loc="46">
        <lem>mārtaṇḍa</lem>
        <rdg source="bib:SubbaRao1956-1958_01">mārt<choice><sic>a</sic><corr>ā</corr></choice>ṇḍa</rdg>
        <note>SR’s emendation is unnecessary.</note>
      </app>
      <app loc="47">
        <lem>nirbhr̥tya-</lem>
        <rdg source="bib:SubbaRao1956-1958_01"><supplied reason="omitted">tan-</supplied>nirbhr̥tya-</rdg>
        <note>If I understand SR’s emendation correctly, then it is more in the nature of a commentary. I do not think any scribal omission happened here. The word <foreign>nirbhr̥tya</foreign> is probably used in the sense of <foreign>nibhr̥ta</foreign> <foreign>naibhr̥tya</foreign>. The same spelling, probably in the same sense, is found in line 20 of the <ref target="DHARMA_INSVengiCalukya00031.xml">Śrīpūṇḍi grant of Tāḻa II</ref>.</note>
      </app>
      <app loc="48">
        <lem>kr̥tvā</lem>
        <rdg source="bib:SubbaRao1956-1958_01">kr̥tyā</rdg>
        <note>Since SR does not emend, I assume this is a typo.</note>
      </app>
      <app loc="48">
        <lem>pe<lb n="50" break="no"/>nuṁbaṟṟu</lem>
        <rdg source="bib:SubbaRao1956-1958_01">pe<lb n="50" break="no"/>nuṁbarru</rdg>
      </app>
      <app loc="53">
        <lem><foreign xml:lang="tel">nūjjuṁ</foreign></lem>
        <rdg source="bib:SubbaRao1956-1958_01"><foreign xml:lang="tel">n<choice><sic>ū</sic><corr>u</corr></choice>jjuṁ</foreign></rdg>
      </app>
      <app loc="53">
        <lem><foreign xml:lang="tel">niduva paduga</foreign></lem>
        <rdg source="bib:SubbaRao1956-1958_01"><foreign xml:lang="tel"><choice><sic>niduva</sic><corr>nirudu</corr></choice> paduga</foreign></rdg>
      </app>
      <app loc="60">
        <lem>cokta<choice><sic>ka</sic><corr>M</corr></choice></lem>
        <rdg source="bib:SubbaRao1956-1958_01">cokt<choice><sic>aka</sic><corr>ā</corr></choice></rdg>
      </app>
      <app loc="60">
        <lem>vasudhā</lem>
        <rdg source="bib:SubbaRao1956-1958_01">vasyadhā</rdg>
      </app>
      <app loc="63">
        <lem><supplied reason="subaudible">’</supplied>yan dharmma-</lem>
        <rdg source="bib:SubbaRao1956-1958_01">ya<choice><sic>n v</sic><corr>d dh</corr></choice>arm<surplus>m</surplus>a-</rdg>
      </app>
      <app loc="66">
        <lem><supplied reason="subaudible">’</supplied>ṁjalir</lem>
        <rdg source="bib:SubbaRao1956-1958_01"><supplied reason="omitted">ṁ</supplied>ja<surplus>ṁ</surplus>lir</rdg>
        <note>I suppose the anusvāra is above <foreign>ja</foreign>, but that is not really a mistake.</note>
      </app>
      
      
    </listApp>
